less, the proportional distribution of any given conversation between the categories can offer useful psychological insights into the mind set of the participants. This is the reason that the majority of conversations are difficult to categorize.\n\n===Functions===\nMost conversations may be classified by their goal.  Conversational ends may, however, shift over the life of the conversation.\n* '''Functional conversation''' is designed to convey information in order to help achieve an individual or group goal.\n* '''[[Small talk]]''' is a type of conversation where the topic is less important than the social purpose of achieving [[human bonding|bonding]] between people or managing [[personal distance]], such as 'how is the weather' might be portrayed as an example, which conveys no practicality whatsoever.\n\n==Aspects==\n\n===Differences between men and women===\n\nA study completed in July 2007 by Matthias Mehl of the [[University of Arizona]] shows that contrary to popular belief, there is little difference in the number of words used by men and women in conversation.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.1139940 |pmid=17615349 |lay-url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn12203-men--the-other-talkative-sex.html |laysource=New Scientist |laydate=July 6, 2007 |title=Are Women Really More Talkative Than Men? |journal=Science |volume=317 |issue=5834 |page=82 |year=2007 |last1=Mehl |first1=M. R. |last2=Vazire |first2=S. |last3=Ramirez-Esparza |first3=N. |last4=Slatcher |first4=R. B. |last5=Pennebaker |first5=J. W. |bibcode=2007Sci...317...82M |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b731be8fdc7f5481f700de45e76c11374c1c716f }}</ref> The study showed that on average each of the sexes uses about 16,000 words per day.\n\n===Between strangers===\nThere are certain situations, typically encountered while traveling, which result in strangers sharing what would ordinarily be an intimate social space such as sitting together on a bus or airplane. In such situations strangers are likely to share intimate personal information they would not ordinarily share with strangers. A special case emerges when one of the travelers is a mental health professional and the other party shares details of their personal life in the apparent hope of receiving help or advice.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/28/business/28psych.html \"Cornered: Therapists on Planes\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814174117/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/28/business/28psych.html |date=14 August 2016 }},  Liz Galst. ''[[The New York Times]]'' 27 September 2010, accessed 28 September 2010</ref>\n\n===Narcissism===\nConversational [[narcissism]] is a term used by sociologist [[Charles Derber]] in his book, ''The Pursuit of Attention: Power and Ego in Everyday Life''.\n\nDerber observed that the social support system in America is relatively weak, and this leads people to compete mightily for attention. In social situations, they tend to steer the conversation away from others and toward themselves. \"Conversational narcissism is the key manifestation of the dominant attention-getting psychology in America,\" he wrote. \"It occurs in informal conversations among friends, family and coworkers. The profusion of popular literature about listening and the etiquette of managing those who talk constantly about themselves suggests its pervasiveness in everyday life.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Derber|first1=Charles|title=The Pursuit of Attention: Power and Ego in Everyday Life|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0195135504|page=19|edition=2nd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OXmOXQPc6eEC&pg=PA19|accessdate=2 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509175038/https://books.google.com/books?id=OXmOXQPc6eEC&pg=PA19|archivedate=9 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhat Derber describes as \"conversational narcissism\" often occurs subtly rather than overtly because it is prudent to avoid being judged an [[Egotism|egotist]].\n\nDerber distinguishes the \"shift-response\" from the \"support-response\". A shift response takes the focus of attention away from the last speaker and refocuses on the new speaker, as in: \"John: I'm feeling really starved. Mary: Oh, I just ate.\" Whereas a support response maintains the focus on the last speaker, as in: \"John: I'm feeling really starved. Mary: When was the last time you ate?\"\n\n===Artificial intelligence===\nThe ability to generate conversation that cannot be distinguished from a human participant has been one test of a successful artificial intelligence (The [[Turing Test]]).  A human judge engages in a natural language conversation with one human and one machine, each of which tries to appear human. If the judge cannot tell the machine from the human, the machine is said to have passed the test. One limitation is that the conversation is limited to a text, not allowing tone to be shown.\n\n===One's self===\nAlso called [[intrapersonal communication]], the act of conversing with oneself can help solve problems or serve therapeutic purposes like avoiding silence.\n\n==In the media==\nAs a prominent and useful figure in most human lives, conversation is often used in the media, e.g. talk shows such as [[William F. Buckley, Jr.|William F. Buckley]]'s [[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]] or the [[Dick Cavett|Dick Cavett Show]].\n\n==Literature==\nAuthors who have written extensively on conversation and attempted to analyze its nature include:\n* Milton Wright wrote ''The Art of Conversation'', a comprehensive treatment of the subject, in 1936.  The book deals with conversation both for its own sake, and for political, sales, or religious ends.  Milton portrays conversation as an art or creation that people can play with and give life to.\n* Kerry Patterson, Joseph Grenny, Al Switzler, and Ron McMillan have written two [[The New York Times Best Seller List|''New York Times'' bestselling]] books on conversation. The first one, ''Crucial Conversations: Tools for Talking When Stakes are High'', McGraw-Hill, 2002, teaches skills for handling disagreement and high-stakes issues at work and at home. The second book, ''Crucial Accountability: Tools for Resolving Violated Expectations, Broken Commitments, and Bad Behavior'', McGraw-Hill, 2013, teaches important skills for dealing with accountability issues.\n*''Difficult Conversations: How to Discuss What Matters Most'' (Viking Penguin, 1999) , a book by Bruce Patton, Douglas Patterson and [[Sheila Heen]] was one of the work products from the [[Harvard Negotiation Project]]. This book built on, and extended the approach developed by [[Roger Fisher (academic)|Roger Fisher]] and \u00a0[[William Ury]] in ''Getting To Yes: Negotiating Agreement Without Giving In'' (Houghton Mifflin, 1981). The book introduced useful concepts such as the Three Conversations ( The 'What Happened' Conversation, The Feelings Conversation, and The Identity Conversation ), Creating a Learning Conversation, and Collaborative Problem Solving.\n* [[Charles Blattberg]] has written two books defending an approach to politics that emphasizes conversation, in contrast to negotiation, as the preferred means of resolving conflict. His ''From Pluralist to Patriotic Politics: Putting Practice First'', Oxford and New York: [[Oxford University Press]], 2000, {{ISBN|0-19-829688-6}}, is a work of political philosophy; and his ''Shall We Dance? A Patriotic Politics for Canada'', Montreal and Kingston: [[McGill-Queen's University Press]], 2003, {{ISBN|0-7735-2596-3}}, applies that philosophy to the Canadian case.\n* Paul Drew & [[John Heritage]] \u2013 ''Talk at Work'', a study of how conversation changes in social and workplace situations.\n* [[Neil Postman]] \u2013 ''[[Amusing Ourselves to Death]]'' (Conversation is not the book's specific focus, but discourse in general gets good treatment here)\n* [[Deborah Tannen]]\n** ''The Argument Culture: Stopping America's War of Words''\n** ''Conversational Style: Analyzing Talk Among Friends'',\n** ''Gender and Discourse''\n** ''I Only Say This Because I Love You''\n** ''Talking from 9 to 5: Women and Men at Work''\n** ''[[That's Not What I Meant!]]''\n** ''[[You Just Don't Understand]]: Women and Men in Conversation''\n* [[Daniel Menaker]] \u2013 ''A Good Talk:  The Story and Skill of Conversation'' (published 2010)\n* Stephen Miller \u2013 ''Conversation: A History of a Declining Art'': provides an extensive history of conversation which dates back to the ancient Greeks with Socrates, and moving forward, to coffeehouses around the world, as well as the modern forces of the electronic age, talk shows, etc.\n\n=== In fiction ===\n* ''[[Conversation in the Cathedral]]'' (1969) is one of the main novels by the Peruvian writer [[Mario Vargas Llosa]].\n\n===In \"Six Benefits of Better Conversation\"===\nThe benefits are:\n# Being better understood\n# Better understanding\n# Better self-confidence\n# Workplace value\n# Better self-care\n# Better relationships<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ekroth|first1=Lauren|title=Six Benefits of Better Conversation|url=http://www.hodu.com/con-benefits.shtml|website=Hodu|accessdate=5 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061030165159/http://hodu.com/con-benefits.shtml|archivedate=30 October 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[A Complete Collection of Genteel and Ingenious Conversation]]'' (book)\n* [[Aizuchi]]\n* [[Awkward silence]]\n* [[Bohm Dialogue]]\n* [[Compulsive talking]]\n* [[Conversation Theory]]\n* [[Conversational narcissism]]\n* [[Richard Sharp (politician)|\"Conversation\" Sharp MP]]<ref>Knapman, D.  ''Conversation Sharp \u2013 The Biography of a London Gentleman, Richard Sharp (1759\u20131835), in Letters, Prose and Verse''. [Private Publication, 2004]. British Library.</ref> Doyen of the Georgian period conversationalists.\n* [[Debate]]\n* [[Dialogue]]\n* [[Discourse]]\n* [[King of Clubs (Whig club)|'King of Clubs']] \u2013 famous Whig conversation club\n* [[Online chat]]\n* [[Small talk]]\n* [[Speech (public address)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{Cite book|isbn=978-0521814263|year=2006|title=Conversation: From Description to Pedagogy|first1=Scott|last1=Thornbury|last2=Slade|first2=Diana|author1link=Scott Thornbury|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V_Q9JnIqqVcC|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Features of Naturalness in Conversation|first=Martin|last=Warren|year=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oCRi-KQN37AC&pg=PT17|isbn=978-9027253958|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Conversation}}\n* [http://www.cnr.berkeley.edu/ucce50/ag-labor/7article/article40.htm Empathic listening skills] How to listen so others will feel heard, or listening first aid ([[University of California]]). Download a one-hour seminar on empathic listening and attending skills.\n* [http://economist.com/printedition/displayStory.cfm?story_id=8345491 \"The art of conversation\", ''Economist'', 19 December 2006]\n\n{{Communication studies|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Oral communication]]\n", "name_user": "Alfiefairest", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammatical errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conversation"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria", "text_new": "{{pp|dispute|small=yes}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria\n| map1            = COVID-19_Outbreak_cases_in_Bulgaria.png\n| legend1         = <center>Number of confirmed cases by province <br/> (as of 31 March)<ref name=\"ESRI\">{{cite web|url=https://esribulgaria.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/6e2c968cf38540f29a4311295dce390f|title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 COVID-19 \u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f|date=28 March 2020|website=ESRI Bulgaria: COVID-19 Tracker|language=bg-BG|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref></center> {{legend|#fefeea|0 confirmed}}{{legend|#F2A88D|1\u201310 confirmed}}{{legend|#E36654|11\u201350 confirmed}}{{legend|#E5354B|51\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#87353F|100+ confirmed}}\n| disease         = [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case      = [[Pleven]], [[Gabrovo]]\n| arrival_date    = 8 March 2020\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]] (globally)<br />local source unknown\n| deaths          = 8\n| website         = [https://www.mh.government.bg/bg/informaciya-za-grazhdani/informaciya-otnosno-noviya-koronavirus-2019-ncov/ Bulgarian Ministry of Health]\n| confirmed_cases = 399\n| recovery_cases  = 17\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Bulgaria]] when the country's first case was confirmed on 8 March 2020. As of 31 March 2020, there are 399 confirmed cases in 21 out of 28 Bulgarian provinces, with 8 recorded deaths and 17 recoveries. A total of 6454 PCR tests had been performed by 26 March.\n\n== Background ==\nA National Crisis-management Staff was formed by the Bulgarian government on 5 March to deal with the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0421\u043f\u0435\u0448\u043d\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0449\u0443 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0430 \u0438 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 (\u041e\u0411\u0417\u041e\u0420) |url=https://nova.bg/news/view/2020/02/24/279057/%D1%81%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%88%D0%BD%D0%B8-%D0%BC%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%BA%D0%B8-%D1%81%D1%80%D0%B5%D1%89%D1%83-%D0%BA%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%80%D1%83%D1%81%D0%B0-%D0%B8-%D1%83-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%81-%D0%BE%D0%B1%D0%B7%D0%BE%D1%80/ |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> The Government has appointed [[Major general|Major General]] [[Professor]] Doctor [[Ventsislav Mutafchiyski]] as the Chairman of the Staff. MG Prof. Dr. Mutafchiyski is the Director of the [[Military Medical Academy (Bulgaria)|Military Medical Academy]] and the most senior medical officer of the [[Bulgarian Armed Forces]]. The MMA combines the military medical services of the country in their entirety with several hospitals in the capital Sofia and around the country. At the same time it is one of the country's leading medical institutions and possesses large medical treatment capacity and know-how. The Staff fulfills a direct operational role in the management of the crisis and its decisions are implemented through executive orders of [[Prime Minister of Bulgaria|Bulgaria's Prime Minister]] and the country's Minister of Health.\n\nOn 23 March a separate Medical Council for dealing with the coronavirus pandemic was appointed by the Prime Minister. The Council is chaired by Professor [[Kosta Kostov]], a leading pulmonary disease expert. The Council's mission is to provide the government with complementary analysis and action proposals and the general public with professional guidance and information. Unlike the National Crisis-management Staff, which is a formal national institution with executive power and tasks, the Council has mostly a knowledge-based advisory role.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u044f\u0442 \u0441\u044a\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0449\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0435 \u0441 COVID-19 |url=https://btvnovinite.bg/bulgaria/prof-kostov-medicinskijat-savet-shte-raboti.html}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== 8 March ===\nOn 8 March 2020 [[Bulgaria]] confirmed its first two cases, a 27-year-old man from [[Pleven]] and a 75-year-old woman from [[Gabrovo]]. Neither of the two reported having traveled to areas with known coronavirus cases. The man tested positive for the virus after being hospitalized for a respiratory infection, and authorities announced plans to test several people who were in contact with the two individuals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/bulgaria-confirms-coronavirus-cases-amid-flu-outbreak/30475539.html|title=Bulgaria, Moldova Report First Coronavirus Cases |date=8 March 2020|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]}}</ref> Two other samples in Pleven and Gabrovo were found positive on 8 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://focus-news.net/news/2020/03/08/2754995/prof-todor-kantardzhiev-ot-pleven-imame-dve-polozhitelni-probi-za-koronavirus-ot-gabrovo-sashto.html|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444. \u0422\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u041a\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0436\u0438\u0435\u0432: \u041e\u0442 \u041f\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0438\u043c\u0430\u043c\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441, \u043e\u0442 \u0413\u0430\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0441\u044a\u0449\u043e|language=Bulgarian|date=8 March 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> [[Index case|Patient zero]] remains unknown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.actualno.com/healthy/oficialno-ima-chetiri-potvyrdeni-sluchaja-na-koronavirus-v-bylgarija-news_1440246.html|title=\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e: \u0418\u043c\u0430 \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0440\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0432\u044a\u0440\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f|date=8 March 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, the hospital in Gabrovo requested additional personnel from other hospitals in the country, as it only had three [[communicable disease]]s specialists. All of its [[internal medicine]] specialists have been quarantined after one of the four initial cases was confirmed to be a nurse at the hospital.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u0430\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0442 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u0435\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0434\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044f \u043d\u0430 Covid-19 |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/gabrovo-poiska-podkreplenie-ot-infektsionisti-zaradi-dvata-sluchaya-na-covid-19 |accessdate=8 March 2020 |date=8 March 2020}}</ref> The government issued a nationwide ban on closed-door public events.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u0441\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0432\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e \u0432 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/politika/pravitelstvoto-zabrani-vsichki-masovi-proyavi-na-zakrito-v-stranata |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> The origin of the outbreak remains unknown, and the [[Ministry of Interior (Bulgaria)|Ministry of Interior]] is tracking down all individuals who have been in contact with the patients.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0427\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0440\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044f \u043d\u0430 COVID-19 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f |url=http://www.vma.bg/newsitem.html?action=news&newsid=829 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> As of 8 March, 254 suspected cases were under quarantine across the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u0414\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0421\u0430\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0430: 254 \u0441\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0430 \u0432 \u0446\u044f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430 |url=http://focus-news.net/news/2020/03/08/2755023/ministar-denitsa-sacheva-254-sa-bolnichnite-listove-s-karantina-za-koronavirusa-v-tsyalata-strana.html |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 10 March ===\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Bulgaria medical cases chart}}\nTwo additional cases were confirmed in Sofia on 10 March 2020: a 74-year-old man and his 66-year-old wife. Both have arrived from [[Lom, Bulgaria|Lom]] two weeks prior to admission.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0417\u0430 \u043e\u0449\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 - \u0432 \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f, \u0441\u044a\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438 \u0411\u043e\u0439\u043a\u043e \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432 |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/za-oshte-dva-sluchaya-na-noviya-virus-u-nas-v-sofiya-saobshti-boyko-borisov |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0416\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0442 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0432 \"\u041f\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0432\" \u0435 \u043d\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043a\u0442\u043d\u0430, \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0432\u0438\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u044a\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u0433\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442 |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/pirogov-e-izoliran-zaradi-dvamata-novi-zarazeni-borisov-svikva-saveta-za-sigurnost |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> The woman died on the next day, becoming the first COVID-19 victim in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432\u0437\u0435 \u043f\u044a\u0440\u0432\u0430 \u0436\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/11/4039345_koronavirusut_vze_purva_jertva_v_bulgariia/ |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 11 March ===\nA suspected case of a 33-year-old man was reported by the Saint George Hospital in [[Plovdiv]] on 11 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=33-\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u0435\u043d \u043c\u044a\u0436 \u043e\u0442 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043e \u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u0418\u043d\u0444\u0435\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0423\u041c\u0411\u0410\u041b \"\u0421\u0432. \u0413\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0438\" \u0432 \u041f\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0434\u0438\u0432 \u0441\u044a\u0441 \u0441\u044a\u043c\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 |url=http://focus-news.net/news/2020/03/11/2756041/33-godishen-mazh-ot-selo-kadievo-e-priet-v-infektsioznata-klinika-na-umbal-sv-georgi-v-plovdiv-sas-samnenie-za-koronavirus.html |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, a 40-year-old woman in [[Varna]] showed COVID-19 symptoms on [[CT scan]], although regional health authorities have not yet confirmed the case.<ref>{{cite news |title=40-\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u0432\u044a\u0432 \u0412\u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430, \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0442 - \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 |url=https://www.dnes.bg/stranata/2020/03/11/40-godishna-pripadna-vyv-varna-predpolagat-koronavirus.441831 |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 12 March ===\nBy 12 March, the number of cases had increased to 23, most of them in Sofia. Many of these had been in contact with the elderly couple admitted to the [[Pirogov Hospital]] on 10 March.\n\n=== 13 March ===\nOn 13 March, after 16 reported cases in one day, Bulgaria declared a state of emergency for one month until 13 April. Schools, shopping centres, cinemas, restaurants, and other places of business were closed. All sports events were suspended. Only supermarkets, food markets, pharmacies, banks and gas stations remain open.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nova.bg/news/view/2020/03/13/281109/\u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f-\u0432-\u0438\u0437\u0432\u044a\u043d\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e-\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435-\u0437\u0430-1-\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0446 |title=\u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0438\u0437\u0432\u044a\u043d\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430 1 \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0446 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |agency=Focus |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Additionally, all arrivals from Italy, Spain, Iran, South Korea and China were placed under a mandatory 14-day quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041c\u0412\u043d\u0420: \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0435 \u0435 \u0432\u044a\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u044a\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0438 |url=https://www.bgonair.bg/a/2-bulgaria/188624-mvnr-balgariya-ne-e-vavela-ogranicheniya-na-darzhavnite-si-granitsi |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> There were 13 breaches of quarantine; patients involved were returned to treatment facilities and warned of repercussions, including fines and prison sentences.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e \u0437\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u043d: 13 \u0434\u0443\u0448\u0438 \u0441\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0434\u044a\u043b\u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0438\u0437\u0434\u0438\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0442 \u0433\u0438 |url=https://dariknews.bg/novini/bylgariia/samo-za-den-13-dushi-sa-narushili-zadylzhitelnata-karantina-izdirvat-gi-video-2216674 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 14 March ===\nOn 14 March, a second death and a third case in Pleven were reported. The second victim of the virus was the 74-year old husband of the first victim.<ref>[https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/14/4040910_vtora_jertva_na_koronavirusa_i_10_novi_zarazeni/ www.dnevnik.bg]</ref>\n\n=== 15 March ===\nThe number of confirmed cases in Bulgaria rose to 51 on 15 March. A total of 83 tests were done at the Military Medical Academy, of which six were positive, and 51 were processed at the National Reference Laboratory, of which two were positive. In Varna, one test out of 12 samples proved positive.\n\n=== 16 March ===\nThe Ministry of Health announced that citizens from a number of countries would be prohibited from entering Bulgaria starting 00:00 on 18 March. These are China, Iran, Bangladesh, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Spain, Italy, South Korea, France, Germany, the Netherlands, Switzerland and the United Kingdom. Additionally, sanitary control units will be established on some border crossings with Serbia, North Macedonia, Greece and Romania.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434 \u0437\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u044f\u0432\u0430 \u0432\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0430 15 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438! |url=https://www.dnes.bg/obshtestvo/2020/03/16/nova-zapoved-zabraniava-vlizane-u-nas-na-grajdani-na-15-strani.442422 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> The number of total cases rose to 62, including two British citizens vacationing in [[Bansko]].\n\n=== 17 March ===\n81 cases were reported, several linked to an outbreak in Bansko. None of the patients were in critical condition.<ref>{{cite news |title=81 \u0441\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/81-sa-veche-zarazenite-s-koronavirus-v-balgariya |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 18 March ===\nThe total number of cases increased to 94 by 18 March, with new cases appearing in [[Smolyan]], [[Veliko Tarnovo]] and [[Pernik]] among recent arrivals from outside the country. The previous day, Bansko became the first town in the country to be put under quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=11 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0438, \u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0441\u0442\u0438\u0433\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044f\u043d \u0438 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e \u0422\u044a\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/11-novi-polozhitelni-probi-virusat-stigna-smolyan-i-veliko-tarnovo |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u041c\u0430\u0439\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0441\u0438\u043d \u0441\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u043e\u0442 \u041f\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u043a |url=https://dnes.dir.bg/obshtestvo/mayka-i-sin-sa-zarazenite-s-koronavirus-ot-pernik |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 19 March ===\nOn 19 March the cases rose to 105 and an 80-year-old woman, who recently had a stroke, died from COVID-19 on the same day, making her the third victim from the disease in Bulgaria.\n\n=== 20 March ===\nThe total number of cases increased to 127 and the first recovery occurred.\n\n=== 21 March ===\nThe number of cases increased to 142 by noon, and three patients had recovered. Two cities, [[Dobrich]] and [[Shumen]], confirmed their first cases, the latter related to the Bansko cluster. There are 84 male and 58 female patients, the youngest being 4 years old, and the oldest 81 years old. More than 5,000 tests had been carried out, and an additional 10,000 tests would be made available at short notice.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u0435\u043d. \u041c\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0444\u0447\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438: 142 \u0441\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 (\u0412\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e) |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/21/4044105_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_izvunrednoto_polojenie/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020 |publisher=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u0418\u0437\u0432\u044a\u043d\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0442\u043d\u043e \u0449\u0435 \u0441\u0435 \u0443\u0434\u044a\u043b\u0436\u0438, \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432}}\n</ref>\n\n=== 24 March ===\nThe cases increased to 218 and the first case in Stara Zagora province was confirmed. A man from the town of [[Kazanlak]] was admitted in the Infectious unit in the hospital in [[Stara Zagora]]. He is believed to be 60 years old and returned from France on the 14th of March.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435 \u0441\u0430 218, \u043f\u044a\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0438 \u0432 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0417\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0430 |url=https://www.bgonair.bg/a/2-bulgaria/189351-zarazenite-s-koronavirus-u-nas-veche-sa-218-parvi-sluchai-v-stara-zagora |publisher= Bulgaria ON AIR |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 25 March ===\nThe number of cases increased to 242 by the end of the day, with the city of [[Sliven]] reporting its first confirmed case. 16 new cases with no relation between them were registered in Sofia, with some being medical staff from a local hospital. Two new cases were confirmed in [[Blagoevgrad]], two in Plovdiv and one in Pleven. Two of the patients who were in critical condition were stabilized but remain \"in stable but severe condition\". One recovered completely, bringing the number of total recoveries to 5. \n\n=== 26 March ===\nA total of 22 cases were reported, bringing the overall number to 264. The coronavirus were registered for the first time in [[Kardzhali]] and [[Haskovo]]. 15 of the newly confirmed cases were in Sofia, 2 in Smolyan, one in Pleven, one in Veliko Tarnovo and one in Varna. Two people were admitted to hospital in critical condition, while three new patients recovered, bringing the number of recovered to 8. Two soldiers were confirmed to have be infected - one was stationed in Kosovo and was immediately brought back to Sofia, and the other contracted the virus in Romania, where he was hospitalised. The national quarantine was extended by additional two weeks and is now expected to finish on April 12.\n\n=== 27 March ===\n29 new cases were registered, with the total number reaching 293. From these, 17 were in Sofia, 5 in Plovdiv, 3 in [[Burgas]], and one each in Varna, [[Kyustendil]], Sliven and [[Pazardzhik]]. At least 93 people remained hospitalized, with 53 in Sofia alone.\n\n=== 28 March ===\nThe total number of cases reached 331, an increase of 38 from the previous day. The new cases included 19 in Sofia, 5 in Blagoevgrad, 4 in Burgas, 3 in Varna, 2 each in Kardzhali, Plovdiv and Shumen, and 1 in Smolyan. Four new deaths were also reported, with two occurring in Blagoevgrad and one each in Kyustendil and Sofia.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0430\u0445\u0430 \u0434\u043e 331 (\u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u044f) |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/28/4047390_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_zarazenite_narasnaha_do_331/ |publisher=Dnevnik |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 29 March ===\nA total of 15 new cases were reported, with 8 in Sofia, 3 in Plovdiv, and one each in Kardzhali, Sliven, Smolyan and Varna. Three new recoveries were also announced, while the number of deaths rose to 8 after a 51-year-old woman died in the Blagoevgrad hospital, one day after her mother had succumbed to the virus. The Ministry of Health announced that 125 out of 324 active cases remain hospitalized, with 13 of those in serious condition. The total number of tests performed exceeded 7,000, with 276 done on 29 March alone.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044a\u0442 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f: \u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0445\u0430 346 |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/29/4047568_koronavirusut_v_bulgariia_zarazenite_stanaha_346/ |publisher=Dnevnik |date=29 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 30 March ===\nThirteen new cases were reported, with seven in Sofia and one each in Blagoevgrad, Kardzhali, Montana, Pleven, Plovdiv and Sliven, for a total of 359 cases. 113 patients remained hospitalized, with 13 in serious condition. Around 56% of all those infected so far were male versus 44% female, with a median age of 45. The total number of recoveries rose to 17.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0417\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0441\u0430 359, \u043d\u044f\u043c\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0438 \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438|url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/30/4048177_zarazenite_v_bulgariia_sa_359_niama_sluchai_v_novi/ |publisher=dnevnik.bg |date=30 March 2020 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=bg-BG}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n=== Cases ===\n{{Side box |metadata=No\n | above = '''Cases of coronavirus in Bulgaria'''\n | abovestyle = text-align:center\n | text = {{Graph:Chart\n  | type = line\n  | linewidth = 1\n  | showSymbols = 1\n  | width = 500\n  | height = 200\n  | showValues = offset:4\n  | xAxisTitle = Date\n  | xAxisAngle = -40\n  | x =8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar\n  | yAxisTitle = No. of cases\n  | y1 = 4, 4, 6, 7, 23, 31, 41, 51, 62, 81, 94, 112, 127, 163, 187, 201, 218, 242, 264, 293, 331,