|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[From the Land of the Moon (film)|From the Land of the Moon]]''\n| Andr\u00e9 Sauvage\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''False Confessions''\n| Dorante\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Redoubtable (film)|Redoubtable]]''\n| [[Jean-Luc Godard]]\n| Nominated\u2014[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actor]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Ismael's Ghosts]]''\n| Ivan Dedalus \n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Un peuple et son roi''\n| [[Robespierre]]\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[At Eternity's Gate (film)|At Eternity's Gate]]''\n| Aurier's Article (voice)\n| \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[A Faithful Man]]''\n| Abel\n| Also writer and director\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Funan (film)|Funan]]''\n| Khuon (voice)\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[An Officer and a Spy (film)|An Officer and a Spy]]''\n|[[Alfred Dreyfus]]\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]''\n| Friedrich Bhaer\n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[The Story of My Wife (film)|The Story of My Wife]]''\n| \n| Post-production\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Rifkin's Festival]]''\n|\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===As filmmaker===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=2 width=\"33\"| Year\n! rowspan=2| Title\n! colspan=2| Credited as\n! rowspan=2| Notes\n|-\n! width=65 |Director\n! width=65 |Screenwriter\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2008\n| align=\"left\"| ''Mes copains''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Short film\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2010\n| align=\"left\"| ''Petit Tailleur''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Short film<br>Nominated\u2014[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Short Film]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2011\n| align=\"left\"| ''La R\u00e8gle de trois''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Short film (also as actor)\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2015\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Two Friends (2015 film)|Two Friends]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Also as actor<br>Nominated\u2014[[2015 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]] - [[Cam\u00e9ra d'Or]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best First Film]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2018\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[A Faithful Man]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Also as actor<br>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other awards===\n*2009: [[Prix Patrick Dewaere]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.louis-garrel.com Official site]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0308039|name=Louis Garrel}}\n\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Most Promising Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrel, Louis}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Most Promising Actor C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:French male child actors]]\n[[Category:French male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Paris]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:French male television actors]]\n[[Category:Conservatoire de Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:French male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:French screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the French National Academy of Dramatic Arts]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:French cinematographers]]\n[[Category:French male stage actors]]\n[[Category:French people of Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French film actor, director, and screenwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Louis Garrel\n| image              = Louis Garrel Cannes 2017.jpg\n| caption            = Garrel at the [[2017 Cannes Film Festival]]\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1983|06|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Paris]], France\n| othername          = \n| occupation         = {{flat list|\n*Actor\n*director \n*screenwriter}}\n| yearsactive        = 1989\u2013present\n| parents            = [[Philippe Garrel]]<br>[[Brigitte Sy]]\n| relations          = {{nowrap|[[Maurice Garrel]] {{small| (paternal grandfather)}}}}\n{{nowrap|[[Esther Garrel]] {{small| (sister)}}}}\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Laetitia Casta]]|2017}}\n| partner            = [[Valeria Bruni Tedeschi]] (2007\u20132012)\n| children           = 1\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Louis Garrel''' (born 14 June 1983) is a French actor and filmmaker. He is best known for his starring role in ''[[The Dreamers (film)|The Dreamers]]'', directed by [[Bernardo Bertolucci]].<ref name=\"lgauteurs\">[http://www.theauteurs.com/cast_members/3375 The Auteurs - Louis Garrel] theauteurs.com</ref><ref name=\"premiere\">Rozemeyer, Karl. [http://www.premiere.com/Feature/Louis-Garrel-Better-in-Threes \"Louis Garrel - Better in Threes\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Premiere.com. March 21, 2008. Retrieved April 5, 2010.</ref> He regularly appears in films by French director [[Christophe Honor\u00e9]], including ''[[Ma M\u00e8re]]'', ''[[Dans Paris]]'', ''[[Love Songs (2007 film)|Love Songs]]'', ''[[The Beautiful Person]]'' and ''[[Making Plans for Lena]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nGarrel was born in Paris, France, the son of director [[Philippe Garrel]] and actress [[Brigitte Sy]] (of sephardic jewish origin).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesinrocks.com/cinema/films-a-l-affiche/petit-tailleur-le-coup-de-foudre-filme-par-louis-garrel/|title=Petit Tailleur, le coup de foudre film\u00e9 par Louis Garrel|date=2010-10-06|website=Les Inrocks|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.franceinter.fr/emissions/l-heure-bleue/l-heure-bleue-25-decembre-2018|title=Transmissions avec Louis et Philippe Garrel|website=www.franceinter.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> His grandfather, [[Maurice Garrel]], and his godfather, [[Jean-Pierre L\u00e9aud]], are also notable French actors.<ref name=\"imdb\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0308039/ Internet Movie Database - Louis Garrel] imdb.com</ref><ref name=\"auteurs\">[http://www.theauteurs.com/cast_members/145 The Auteurs - Philippe Garrel] theauteurs.com</ref> He is a graduate of the [[Conservatoire de Paris]].<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Career==\nGarrel was six when he first appeared onscreen, in the film ''[[:fr:Les Baisers de secours|Les Baisers de secours]]''.<ref name=\"lgauteurs\"/> Twelve years later, he appeared in his second film, ''[[:fr:Ceci est mon corps|Ceci est mon corps]]''.\n\nIn 2002, Garrel gained international recognition playing [[Eva Green]]'s twin brother in ''[[The Dreamers (film)|The Dreamers]]''.<ref name=\"premiere\"/> Director [[Bernardo Bertolucci]] found him on the first session of casting in [[Paris]].<ref>Morales, Wilson. [http://www.blackfilm.com/20040130/features/bertolucci.shtml \"''The Dreamers'': An Interview with Bernardo Bertolucci\"], Blackfilm.com. 2004. Retrieved April 5, 2010.</ref> Garrel has since starred in various French films, including ''[[Regular Lovers (film)|Les Amants r\u00e9guliers]]'' (2005), directed by his father Philippe Garrel. He was awarded the [[C\u00e9sar Award for Most Promising Actor]] for his work in the film.<ref name=\"lgauteurs\"/><ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nGarrel has collaborated five times with filmmaker [[Christophe Honor\u00e9]] in the feature films ''[[Ma M\u00e8re]]'' (2004), an adaptation of the eponymous novel by [[Georges Bataille]] starring [[Isabelle Huppert]]; ''[[Dans Paris]]'' (2006), alongside [[Romain Duris]]; ''[[Love Songs (2007 film)|Love Songs]]'' (2007), a film for which he also revealed his talent as a singer<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.rfi.fr/actufr/articles/089/article_51980.asp|title=RFI - Cin\u00e9ma - Quand l'amour se chante et se pleure|website=www1.rfi.fr}}</ref>; ''[[The Beautiful Person]]'' (2008); ''[[Making Plans for Lena]]'' (2009) and finally, ''[[Two Friends (2015 film)|Two Friends]]'' (2015), where Honor\u00e9 served as co-writer. He also appeared in [[Valeria Bruni Tedeschi]]'s ''[[Actrices]]'' (2007), Rachid Hami's ''Choisir d'aimer'' (2008) and Philipe Garrel's ''[[Frontier of the Dawn]]'' (2008). \n\nIn 2008, he launched into directing with his first short film, ''Mes copains''. Two years later, he directed a second short film, ''Petit Tailleur''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/louis-garrel_893741.html|title=Louis Garrel confirme ses talents de cin\u00e9aste avec Petit tailleur|date=May 21, 2010|website=LExpress.fr}}</ref> \n\nHe appeared in ''[[Heartbeats (film)|Heartbeats]]'', the second film by director [[Xavier Dolan]], released in 2010. In 2011, Garrel directed a third short film, ''La R\u00e8gle de trois'', with [[Vincent Macaigne]] and [[Golshifteh Farahani]], which he presented at the [[Locarno Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http://blogs.lesinrocks.com/locarno/2011/08/10/siankowski-a-locarno-il-a-neige-sur-le-lac-majeur-suite-et-fin/|title=Wikiwix's cache|website=archive.wikiwix.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he played [[Jacques de Bascher]], the lover of [[Karl Lagerfeld]] and [[Yves Saint Laurent (designer)|Yves Saint Laurent]] in [[Bertrand Bonello]]'s film, ''[[Saint Laurent (film)|Saint Laurent]]''.\n\nHis directional debut film, ''[[Two Friends (2015 film)|Two Friends]]'', starring Golshifteh Farahani, [[Vincent Macaigne]] and himself<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/article/fichearticle_gen_carticle=18627267.html|title=Le premier long m\u00e9trage de Louis Garrel, c'est pour bient\u00f4t !|website=AlloCin\u00e9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/cinema/2014/06/03/03002-20140603ARTFIG00328-louis-garrel-offre-un-role-a-sa-compagne-dans-les-deux-amis.php|title=Louis Garrel offre un r\u00f4le \u00e0 sa compagne dans Les Deux Amis|first=El\u00e9onore|last=Prieur|date=June 3, 2014|website=Le Figaro.fr}}</ref>, was released in cinemas in 2015.\n\n==Personal life==\nAside from his native [[French language|French]], Garrel speaks [[English language|English]] and [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nGarrel was in a relationship with [[Valeria Bruni Tedeschi]] from 2007 to 2012. She is the elder sister of [[Carla Bruni]], the wife of the former French president, Nicolas Sarkozy. In 2009 Bruni Tedeschi and Garrel adopted a baby from [[Senegal]], whom they named C\u00e9line.<ref>Boivin, Justine. [http://www.gala.fr/l_actu/on_ne_parle_que_de_ca/carla_sarkozy_et_valeria_bruni-tedeschi_complexes_mais_pas_complices_136380 \"Tout oppose les deux s\u0153ur\"], ''Gala'', 14 October 2008. Retrieved April 5, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Garrel married model and actress [[Laetitia Casta]] and became stepfather to her three children. The couple have been together since 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/style/laetitia-casta-marries-louis-garrel/|title=French Model Laetitia Casta Is Married! Get All the Details on the Secret Ceremony|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===As actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Les Baisers de secours'' \n| Lo\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Ceci est mon corps''\n| Antoine\n|\n|-\n|  2002\n| ''The War in Paris'' (''La Guerre \u00e0 Paris'')\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[The Dreamers (film)|The Dreamers]]''\n| Theo\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Ma m\u00e8re]]''\n| Pierre\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Regular Lovers (film)|Regular Lovers]]'' \n| Fran\u00e7ois Dervieux\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Most Promising Actor]]<br>Etoiles d'Or for Best Male Newcomer \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Dans Paris]]''\n| Jonathan\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''A Curtain Raiser'' (''Un lever de rideau'')\n| Bruno\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Love Songs (2007 film)|Love Songs]]'' \n| Isma\u00ebl B\u00e9noliel\n| Nominated\u2014[[3rd Globes de Cristal Award|Globes de Cristal Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Actrices]]'' \n| \u00c9ric\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Choisir d'aimer''\n| Pascal\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Frontier of the Dawn]]'' \n| Fran\u00e7ois\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Beautiful Person]]'' \n| Jacques Nemours\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Making Plans for Lena]]'' \n| Simon\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Le Mariage \u00e0 trois''\n| Th\u00e9o\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Heartbeats (film)|Heartbeats]]''\n| Guest in the final scene\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Diarchy''\n|\n| Short film written and directed by Ferdinando Cito Filomarino\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Beloved (2011 film)|Beloved]]'' \n| Cl\u00e9ment\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''La R\u00e8gle de trois'' \n| Louis \n| Short film (also as director and screenwriter)<br>[[Prix Jean Vigo]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[A Burning Hot Summer]]'' \n| Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric \n|\n|-\n| 2012\n|''Les coquillettes''\n| Louis Garrel \n|\n|-\n| 2013\n|''[[A Castle in Italy]]''\n| Nathan\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n|''[[Jealousy (2013 film)|Jealousy]]''\n| Louis \n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Saint Laurent (film)|Saint Laurent]]''\n| Jacques de Bascher \n| Nominated\u2014[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[L'Astragale]]''\n| Jacky\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[In the Shadow of Women]]''\n| Narrator (voice)\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Mon roi]]''\n| Solal\n| Nominated\u2014[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Two Friends (2015 film)|Two Friends]]''\n| Abel \n| Also as director and screenwriter\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Planetarium (film)|Planetarium]]''\n| Andr\u00e9 Korben\n| \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[From the Land of the Moon (film)|From the Land of the Moon]]''\n| Andr\u00e9 Sauvage\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''False Confessions''\n| Dorante\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Redoubtable (film)|Redoubtable]]''\n| [[Jean-Luc Godard]]\n| Nominated\u2014[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actor]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Ismael's Ghosts]]''\n| Ivan Dedalus \n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Un peuple et son roi''\n| [[Robespierre]]\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[At Eternity's Gate (film)|At Eternity's Gate]]''\n| Aurier's Article (voice)\n| \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[A Faithful Man]]''\n| Abel\n| Also writer and director\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Funan (film)|Funan]]''\n| Khuon (voice)\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[An Officer and a Spy (film)|An Officer and a Spy]]''\n|[[Alfred Dreyfus]]\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]''\n| Friedrich Bhaer\n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[The Story of My Wife (film)|The Story of My Wife]]''\n| \n| Post-production\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Rifkin's Festival]]''\n|\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===As filmmaker===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=2 width=\"33\"| Year\n! rowspan=2| Title\n! colspan=2| Credited as\n! rowspan=2| Notes\n|-\n! width=65 |Director\n! width=65 |Screenwriter\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2008\n| align=\"left\"| ''Mes copains''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Short film\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2010\n| align=\"left\"| ''Petit Tailleur''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Short film<br>Nominated\u2014[[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Short Film]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2011\n| align=\"left\"| ''La R\u00e8gle de trois''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Short film (also as actor)\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2015\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Two Friends (2015 film)|Two Friends]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Also as actor<br>Nominated\u2014[[2015 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]] - [[Cam\u00e9ra d'Or]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best First Film]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2018\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[A Faithful Man]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Also as actor<br>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other awards===\n*2009: [[Prix Patrick Dewaere]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.louis-garrel.com Official site]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0308039|name=Louis Garrel}}\n\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Most Promising Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrel, Louis}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Most Promising Actor C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:French male child actors]]\n[[Category:French male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Paris]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:French male television actors]]\n[[Category:Conservatoire de Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:French male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:French screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the French National Academy of Dramatic Arts]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:French cinematographers]]\n[[Category:French male stage actors]]\n", "name_user": "Arslan-San", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis_Garrel"}
{"title_page": "Say So (Doja Cat song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Say So\n| cover      = Say So - Doja Cat.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = \n| artist     = [[Doja Cat]]\n| type       = single\n| album      = [[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]\n| released   = January 28, 2020\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   = 2019\n| genre      = <!-- Sourced in the \"Composition\" section. -->\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"Nylon\">{{cite web |last1=Wang |first1=Steffanee |title=Doja Cat's \"Say So\" Enters Billboard Hot 100, Thanks To TikTok |url=https://nylon.com/doja-cat-tiktok-say-so |website=[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]] |date=January 15, 2020 |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[pop-rap]]<ref name=\"The Oprah Magazine\">{{cite web |last1=Janes |first1=DeAnna |title=Who Is Doja Cat? All About the Artist Behind \"Say So\" |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a31123906/who-is-doja-cat/ |website=[[O, The Oprah Magazine|The Oprah Magazine]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[disco]]<ref name=\"The Oprah Magazine\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Sam |title=With Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love', Theatrical Pop Is Once Again Taking Over The Charts |url=https://junkee.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-pop/245988 |website=[[Junkee]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=March 10, 2020 |quote=[...] Doja Cat has nabbed a viral hit with disco tune 'Say So'.}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:58\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Kemosabe Records|Kemosabe]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Doja Cat|Amalaratna Zandile Dlamini]]|Lydia Asrat|[[Lukasz Gottwald]]|Yeti Beats}}\n| producer   = [[Dr. Luke|Tyson Trax]]\n| prev_title = [[Boss Bitch (Doja Cat song)|Boss Bitch]]\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title = Like That\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|pok8H_KF1FA|\"Say So\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Say So'''\" is a song by American rapper and singer [[Doja Cat]], featured on her second studio album ''[[Hot Pink (album)|Hot Pink]]'' (2019). It was sent to American radio on January 28, 2020 as the album's fifth single. The song was written by Doja Cat, Lydia Asrat, Yeti Beats and [[Dr. Luke|Lukasz Gottwald]]. The song was produced by [[Tyson Trax]]. It gained popularity after a dance created by [[TikTok]] user Haley Sharpe went viral on the platform.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web |last1=Mamo |first1=Heran |title=Here Are the Lyrics to Doja Cat's 'Say So' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lyrics/8548599/doja-cat-say-so-lyrics |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=January 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"buzzfeed-dance\"/> The song has so far peaked at number nine on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Doja Cat's first top 10 single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9346375/weeknd-blinding-lights-number-one-hot-100|title=The Weeknd's 'Blinding Lights' Hits No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100, Doja Cat's 'Say So' Enters Top 10|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\"Say So\" was originally released as the fifth track on Doja Cat's second studio album ''Hot Pink''.<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/reviews/doja-cat-hot-pink|title=Doja Cat - Hot Pink - Clash Magazine|last=Bashford|first=Erin|date=November 8, 2019|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Elle\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/a29737190/doja-cat-hot-pink-album-interview/|title=Doja Cat Just Wants To Make Rap Colorful|last1=Penrose|first1=Nerisha|website=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> During late 2019 and early 2020, the song gained popularity on the social media app [[TikTok]] due to several dance challenge videos that featured the song.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> Following this, the song was sent to United States [[contemporary hit radio]] as an official single from the album.<ref name =\"US Date\"/>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Say So\" has been described as a \"steamy, groovy\"<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> [[pop music|pop]],<ref name=\"Nylon\">{{cite web |last1=Wang |first1=Steffanee |title=Doja Cat's \"Say So\" Enters Billboard Hot 100, Thanks To TikTok |url=https://nylon.com/doja-cat-tiktok-say-so |website=[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]] |date=January 15, 2020 |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref> [[pop-rap]],<ref name=\"The Oprah Magazine\">{{cite web |last1=Janes |first1=DeAnna |title=Who Is Doja Cat? All About the Artist Behind \"Say So\" |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a31123906/who-is-doja-cat/ |website=[[O, The Oprah Magazine|The Oprah Magazine]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> and [[disco]]<ref name=\"The Oprah Magazine\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Sam |title=With Lady Gaga's 'Stupid Love', Theatrical Pop Is Once Again Taking Over The Charts |url=https://junkee.com/lady-gaga-stupid-love-pop/245988 |website=[[Junkee]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=March 10, 2020 |quote=[...] Doja Cat has nabbed a viral hit with disco tune 'Say So'.}}</ref> song. According to the sheet music of the song published at Musicnotes.com by [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]], \"Say So\" is composed in the key of [[D Major]] and follows a [[Tempo]] of 116 beats per minute.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0207459|title=Doja Cat \"Say So\" Sheet Music in D Major (transposable)|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Musicnotes.com|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The song additionally draws inspiration from 1970s [[funk]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amp.popbuzz.com/music/news/doja-cat-say-so-misheard-lyrics/|title=You've been singing Doja Cat\u2019s \"Say So\" lyrics wrong this whole time|author=Thompson, Sophie|website=PopBuzz|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nIn her review for ''Hot Pink'', Lucy Shanker of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' deemed the song a \"traditional pop hit\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/11/album-review-doja-cat-hot-pink/|title=Doja Cat Scratches at Her Potential on the Mixed Hot Pink|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Shanker|first=Lucy|date=November 16, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref> Nerisha Penrose of ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' wrote that the song \"offers a healthy dose of nostalgia as Doja's hushed, airy voice floats over a bed of iridescent synths and a funky bassline\".<ref name = \"Elle\"/> ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]'' wrote that the song is \"tied together with Doja's always perfect vocal performance\".<ref name = \"Clash\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nFollowing several viral dance challenge videos that featured the song, \"Say So\" became a [[sleeper hit]] on the record charts in a number of countries prior to being serviced as a single in late January. \n\nIn the United States, \"Say So\" initially entered the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100]] at number 19 on the chart issue dated January 4, 2020, where it moved up to number six the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/charts/bubbling-under-hot-100-singles/2020-01-04|title=Music: Billboard Bubbling Under Hot 100 Chart|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/charts/bubbling-under-hot-100-singles/2020-01-11|title=Music: Billboard Bubbling Under Hot 100 Chart|publisher=}}</ref> After two weeks, \"Say So\" earned Doja Cat her third [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] entry, and second from the parent album ''Hot Pink'', debuting at number 95 on the chart dated January 18, 2020. It jumped to number 77 in its second week on the chart, and gradually climbed up the chart. It subsequently started at number 33 on the [[Mainstream Top 40]], becoming her second single to chart on pop airplay following \"[[Juicy (Doja Cat song)|Juicy]]\"; it has since risen to a peak of number 11 on the chart.<ref name=\"Pop Songs\"/> Following the release of its music video, \"Say So\" ascended 18 positions to number 33 on the Hot 100 in its eighth week charting, while placing number 26 on Streaming Songs. It further reached number nine on the Hot 100, becoming her highest charting single so far.<ref name=\"Hot 100\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/streaming-songs|title=Music: Billboard Streaming Songs Chart|work=Billboard}}</ref> Consequently, it marked Doja Cat's first top 40 single in the country, surpassing the number 41 peak of \"Juicy\". It charted at number nine on the [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]].\n\nOutside of the United States, \"Say So\" peaked within the top ten of the charts in Australia, Belgium, the Netherlands, New Zealand, the Republic of Ireland and the United Kingdom. It has also peaked within the top forty in countries including Greece and Slovakia. \n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Say So\" entered the [[UK Singles Chart]] at number 83 on January 3, 2020 \u2013 for the week ending date January 9, 2020. It gradually ascended through the chart, cracking the top 40 at number 35 on February 7, 2020 \u2013 for the week ending date February 13, 2020. It entered the top 20 at number nineteen on February 22, 2020 \u2013 for the week ending February 28, 2020. The following week, it entered the top ten.\n\n==Live performances==\nThe song was performed by Doja on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'', on February 26, 2020. The performance features Doja Cat dressed in a baby pink bodysuit, along with two backup singers/dancers who execute disco-influenced choreography, which incorporated some of the dance moves from the viral TikTok routine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/doja-cat-delivers-sultry-say-so-performance-for-tonight-show-news.104862.html|title=Doja Cat Delivers Fun & Sultry \"Say So\" Performance For \"Tonight Show\"|website=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"Say So\" was released on February 27, 2020. It is \"[[disco]]-era\" themed set in late 1970s [[Los Angeles]], and filmed at the [[Sheats\u2013Goldstein Residence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3157849/doja-cat-say-so-video/|title=Doja Cat's 'Say So' Video Is A Shimmering, Disco-Era Thirst Trap|website=[[MTV]]|last=Roth|first=Madeline|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> In the video, directed by [[Hannah Lux Davis]], Doja appears in several different \"shimmery\" outfits and walks a tiger with a leash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/02/27/doja-cat-say-so-video/|title=Doja Cat Goes Disco in 'Say So' Video|website=Rap-Up|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> The video features Josu\u00e9 de La Vega as Doja's love interest and features cameo appearances from [[TikTok]] stars Dont\u00e8 Colley and Haley Sharpe, the latter of whom created the viral dance for the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nylon.com/doja-cat-say-so-video|title=Doja Cat Enlists Haley Sharpe And Dont\u00e9 Colley For \"Say So\" Video|website=Nylon|last=Halabian|first=Layla|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> The dance itself, which made the song popular, was featured in the music video.<ref name=\"buzzfeed-dance\">{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/laurenstrapagiel/doja-cat-say-so-tiktok-dance-haley-sharpe|title=A TikTok Dance Has Made The Jump To An Actual Music Video|website=Buzzfeed|last=Strapagiel|first=Lauren|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n'''Jax Jones Midnight Snack Remix'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Say So (Jax Jones Midnight Remix) - Single on Apple Music |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/say-so-jax-jones-midnight-snack-remix/1499028545?i=1499028816 |website=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n#\"Say So\" ([[Jax Jones]